4.1 Quantitative variable:Price

Boxplot of Price

ggplot(data = df) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = 1,y = price))+
  ggtitle('Price of Real Estate Market')+
  labs(x = '', y = 'Price')+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar)+
  theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank(),#delete the x axis lables
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),# title center
        text =  element_text(size=15),plot.margin = margin(2,1.5,2,1.5, "cm"))

We can see from the graph, there are many outliers. So we can tell there are some properties whose prices are much higher than the average of the market in our samples. The question is what causes these properties price so high.

medprice_yrbuilt_yrreno<-grid.arrange(

Question: Why is there a drop in median price from view 1 to 2?

To investigate why there was a drop in median price from condition 3 to 4 and view 1 to 2, we decide to see if grid tile will give us an explanation

df %>%
group_by(condition, view) %>% 
  summarise(med_sqft = median(sqft_living)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(condition, view)) + 
  geom_tile(aes(fill = med_sqft))

We can see that the median sqft for the grid (4,2) falls around 2000 sqft, so there is less median sqft available for those houses so the median prices drop. No further questions.

    facet_wrap( ~ as.integer(floors))+

Floor gives us a more consistent pattern than bathroom throughout. So, Floor is a better predictor for median prices than bathroom.
